{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> ὕπερος</b>, ὁ, <br /> or <u><b>ὕπερον</b></u>, τό, see below:— <b>pestle,</b> ὕπερον δὲ τρίπηχυν [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus “Opera et Dies” 423; λεήναντες ὑπέροισι 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.200 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ὑπέρου μοι περιτροπὴ γενήσεται, proverbial of never-ending and ineffectual labour, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Comicus 1, compare 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Theaetetus” 209e, 4th-3rd c.BC: Philemo Comicus 30, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus 2.1072b; so εἰ ἐς ὅλμον ὕδωρ ἐκχέας ὑπέρῳ σιδηρῷ πτίττοι 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Herm.” 79; ὕπερα σιδηρᾶ 2nd c.AD(?): Pollianus Epigrammaticus 7.107, with which Bgk. compared.. έροις σιδηροῖς,\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] the mutilated title of a successful comedy in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “IG” 14.1097. \">Refs</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__II</b></Level2> <b>anything shaped like a pestle,</b> <br /><Level3><b>__II.1</b></Level3> <b>club, cudgel,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Alexander” 63, 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Demon.” 48. \">Refs 1st c.AD+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__II.2</b></Level3> <b>lever for stretching dislocated joints,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ ἀγμῶν” 13, +others \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level2><b>__III</b></Level2> like{πηνίον}, a pupa of a geometrid moth, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Aristoteles Philosophus “Historia Animalium” 551b6.\">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]—The form <b>ὕπερον</b>, τό, is found in [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" “Hesperia” 5.383 (Athens, 5th c.BC, _plural_), 5th c.BC: Hippocrates Medicus “περὶ ἄρθρων ἐμβολῆς” 5, 78, 2nd c.BC: Polybius Historicus 1.22.7, “PRyl.” 167.14 (_plural_, 1st c.AD), 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Philops.” 35, 2nd c.AD(?): Pollianus Epigrammaticus 1.245, 7.107, 10.114, “Etymologicum Magnum” 779.48 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; whereas none of the other passages in which the word occurs prove anything about the gender, except [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th-7th c.BC: Hesiodus Epicus [same place] \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; whence it has been suggested that τρίπηχυ should be read there, and ὕπερον, τό, received as the only form.","strongNumber":"G9555","accentedUnicode":"ὕπερον","shortDef":"a pestle","mediumDef":"a pestle","stepGloss":"a pestle","stepTransliteration":"huperon","_step_Type":"word"}]}